2. Preparation of Training Dataset from extracted ROIs¶

We can use any version of ENVI for marking training pixels for each class and extract the sub images for individual classes. Here we can first convert the extracted image into csv(comma separated value) file and use it for improving quality of training data.

Load the hyperspeclib library¶

In [2]:
from hyspeclib import prepare_training_data

Define all the paths¶

In [26]:
our_data_dir = 'anand/'

## Path to the diretory containing extracted images
our_raw_data = our_data_dir+'/Raw_training/'

## Path to save raw training data in .csv file 
save_path_with_raw = our_data_dir+'Training_dataset/Handpicked/train_with_outliers_new.csv'

## Path to save refined training data in .csv format 
save_path_refined = our_data_dir+'Training_dataset/Handpicked/train_without_outliers_new.csv'

Extracting Training data¶

You can specify the bands to be removed if ROIs are exctrated from an unprocessed image using envi, if not then all bands will be included in result.

In [3]:
noisy_bands = [0, 1, 2, 196, 197, 198, 199, 200, 201, 202, 203, 290, 291, 292, 293, 294, 295, 296, 297, 298, 299, 300, 301, 302, 303, 304, 305, 306, 307, 308, 309, 310, 311, 312]
In [4]:
prep = prepare_training_data(img_source_dir=our_raw_data,save_path=save_path_with_raw,noisy_bands=noisy_bands)
In [9]:
prep.extract()

Once the .csv file for raw training data points are ready, note the list of crop labels from above output for further use.

In [10]:
crop_list = ['Castor', 'Dry_Fallow', 'Fallow', 'Linseed', 'Shadow', 'Shrub_Orchard', 'Tobacco_Peak', 'Wet_Fallow', 'Wheat', 'Wheat_Soft_Dough']

Refining quality of training dataset¶

We can use this module to visualise the training points selected manually in 2D form genereted by RED vs NIR chennels. We can refine the pixels for each class by setting the left, right, top and bottom thresold of reflectance value.

In [11]:
prep.outlier_analysis(data_path=save_path_with_raw , class_labels=crop_list)


------------------- Instructions -------------------


1. Use the visualise() method to plot two dimention representation of crops.

2. Use the remove_outliers() method to remove outliers. You can pass external limits with

 rules = { 1:[0,0,0,0],2:[0,0,0,0]} as argument.

 You can pass Left, Right, Top, Bottom limits for manually remove outliers for any crop.
 

3. Use save() method to save data after outlier removal.

Before refining data¶

In [12]:
prep.visualise()

After refining data¶

In [25]:
prep.remove_outlier({2:[0,0.145,0,0],3:[0.14,0,0,0], 4:[0,0.05,0,0], 6:[0,0.05,0.23,0] })

Save refined data to new file¶

In [27]:
prep.save(path_to_save=save_path_refined)
